04777nam a22007215i 9781782048381DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817820483817 a10.1515/97817820483812doi  a(DE-B1597)676474  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aARC0050002bisacsh04a724qOCoLC223/eng/202302161 aLindfield, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGeorgian Gothic :bMedievalist Architecture, Furniture and Interiors, 1730-1840 /cPeter Lindfield. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (282 p.) :b59 b/w, 11 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMedievalism ;v800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: the Gothic Aesthetic in Britain and British Furniture, 1730–1840 -- t1 Understanding Gothic Architecture in Georgian Britain -- t2 Creation of Classical Gothic Architecture, Furniture and Interiors -- t3 High Fashion and Fragments of the Past: the Omnipresence of Rococo Gothic -- t4 Fluctuating Tastes: Gothic in Later Eighteenth-century Britain -- t5 The ‘Chaos of Modern Gothic Excrescences’: Regency to Revolution -- tConclusion -- tAppendix -- tBibliography -- tGlossary -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFirst full-length study of the impact of the Gothic Revival across the arts, from literature and architectural theory to houses, furniture and interiors.The Gothic Revival, rich, ambitious, occasionally eccentric, but nonetheless visually exciting, is one of Britain's greatest contributions to early modern design history, not least because for the most part it contravened approvedtaste: Classicism. Scholars have tended to treat Georgian Gothic as an homogenous and immature precursor to "high" Victorian Gothic, and centred their discussion around Walpole's Strawberry Hill. This book, conversely, reveals how the style was imaginatively and repeatedly revised and incorporated into prevailing eighteenth-century fashions: Palladianism, Rococo, Neoclassicism, and antiquarianism. It shows how under the control of architects, from Wren toPugin, Walpole and Cottingham, and furniture designs, especially those of Chippendale, and Ince and Mayhew, a shared language of Gothic motifs was applied to British architecture, furniture and interiors. Georgian Britain was awash with Gothic forms, even if the arbiters of taste criticised it vehemently. Throughout, the volume reframes the Gothic Revival's expression by connecting it with Georgian understandings of the medieval past, and consequently revises our interpretation of one of the most influential, yet lampooned, forms of material culture at the time. Peter N. Lindfield is a Leverhulme Early Career Research Fellow at the University of Stirling.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGothic revival (Architecture)y18th century. 0aMedievalism in architecturey18th century. 4aArchaeology & Heritage. 4aArt & Architecture. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aModern History. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh  aBritish rchitecture.  aGeorgian design.  aGothic architecture.  aGothic revival.  aGothic style.  aarchitecture.  aart and design studies.  aclassicism.  aeightenth century.  afashion.  ahistory of design.  ainterior design.  anineteenth century.  astyles.  atrends.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204838140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782048381423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782048381/original  a978-3-11-143131-4  Boydell a